'''Andre David Sennwald''' (August 4, 1907 — Jan 12, 1936) was a [[Film criticism|motion picture critic]] for ''[[The New York Times]]''.

==Life==
After graduating from [[Columbia University School of Journalism]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=FE0bAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9EsEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2829%2C3966440|title=New York Critic Killed By Blast|date=Jan 13, 1936|via= Google News Archive Search|publisher=The Pittsburgh Press |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> Sennwald was hired as a reporter for ''The New York Times'' in 1930. As the film critic [[Mordaunt Hall]] gave up his post in October 1934, Sennwald became his successor.<ref name="KauffmannHenstell1972">{{cite book|author1=Stanley Kauffmann|authorlink1=Stanley Kauffmann|author2=Bruce Henstell|title=American film criticism, from the beginnings to Citizen Kane: reviews of significant films at the time they first appeared|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aWpZAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Andre+Sennwald|accessdate=26 December 2016|year=1972|publisher=Liveright|isbn=978-0-87140-557-9|page=308}}</ref>

He lived at 670 West End Avenue, [[Upper West Side]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8008258/gotham_film_critic_killed_by_gas_blast/|title=Gotham Film Critic Killed By Gas Blast|work=The Index-Journal|location=Greenwood, South Carolina|date=
13 Jan 1936|page=1|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> He was married to the former Yvonne {{sic|Beaudry}}.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8008455/police_investigate_gas_death_of_film/|title=Police Investigate Gas Death of Film Critic;Hint Suicide|work=The Brooklyn Daily Eagle|date=13 Jan 1936|page=2|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref>

He died on January 12, 1936 as a result of [[gas poisoning]] before his penthouse apartment exploded because of a [[gas leak]].<ref name=montreal>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=zn4tAAAAIBAJ&sjid=5pgFAAAAIBAJ&pg=3565%2C1353482|title=Andre Sennwald Killed|via=Google News Archive Search|publisher=The Montreal Gazette|date=Jan 13, 1936|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8008031/found_dead_in_debris/|title=Found Dead in Debris|work=The Ottawa Journal|date=13 Jan 1936|page=13|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> The explosion wrecked the penthouse and the top three floors of the 17-story building.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8008192/penthouse_wrecked_by_blast_one_killed/|title=Penthouse Wrecked By Blast; One Killed|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|date=12 Jan 1936|page=11|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref>
Sennwald had an appointment with his ex-wife Yvonne Beaudray and did not appear, which is why she went to see him, only to find him dead in the ruins of his home. Since Sennwald was believed by friends to be in good health<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Wc4gAAAAIBAJ&sjid=6moFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5488%2C1010659|title=Andre Sennwald Found Dead After Explosion|via= Google News Archive Search|publisher=The Lewiston Daily Sun|date=Jan 13, 1936 |accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref> and no suicide note was found, nor was one ever officially released, whether it was an accident or a suicide is unknown.<ref name=montreal/>

His last review was for ''[[The Ghost Goes West]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/8008634/the_last_quote/|title=The last quote|work=Reading Times|location=Reading, Pennsylvania|date=16 Jan 1936|page=6|via=Newspapers.com|accessdate=26 December 2016}}</ref>

His successor as chief film critic of the New York Times was [[Frank Nugent]].

