This is a list of '''massacres in the [[Italian Social Republic]]''' in which there were more than 100 victims. German troops in Italy often massacred civilians in retaliation for partisan activity.<ref>{{cite news |date= |title=Massacres with more than 100 victims|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=349 |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref>
To a lesser extent, war crimes were committed by the [[National Republican Army]] (fascist Italian army), usually against [[Italian resistance movement|Italian partisans]], such as at the [[Salussola massacre]], where 20 partisans were executed. Partisans, in retaliation, sometimes also massacred captured Fascist soldiers, like at the [[Rovetta massacre]].
==List of massacres== A list of massacres of either more than 100 victims or international notability: {|class="sortable wikitable" style="font-size:90%;" |- ! style="width:120px;"|Name ! style="width:65px;"|Date ! style="width:120px;"|Location ! style="width:30px;"|Deaths ! style="width:120px;"|Perpetrators !class="unsortable"|Notes |- |[[Lake Maggiore massacres]] |September & October 1943 |[[Lago Maggiore]] |{{hs|00056}}56 |[[1st SS Panzer Division Leibstandarte SS Adolf Hitler|1st SS Panzer Division]] |Murder of 56 predominantly Italian Jews despite strict German orders not to carry out any violence against civilians, also noted for the controversial court case in West Germany in the late 1960s.<ref name= "Statuelimit" >{{cite news |last=Kellerhoff |first=Sven Felix|date=7 January 2008|title=Fünf SS-Verbrecher werden angeklagt |trans-title=Five SS criminals put on trial |url=https://www.welt.de/politik/article1527417/Fuenf-SS-Verbrecher-werden-angeklagt.html# |language=German |work=[[Die Welt]] |location= |access-date=27 September 2018 }}</ref><ref name="Urteil" >{{cite web |url=https://www.jurion.de/urteile/bgh/1970-03-17/5-str-218_69/ |title=Bundesgerichtshof Urt. v. 17.03.1970, Az.: 5 StR 218/69 |publisher= |date=17 March 1970 |website= |access-date=27 September 2018 |language=German |trans-title=German High Court verdict from 17 March 1970}}</ref> |- |[[Boves massacre]] |19 September 1943 |[[Boves, Piedmont|Boves]] |{{hs|00023}}23 |[[1st SS Panzer Division Leibstandarte SS Adolf Hitler|1st SS Panzer Division]] |Massacre of 23 civilians in retaliation of the capture of two German soldiers despite the two having been freed in exchange for the promise that no reprisal against civilians would be carried out. Sometimes incorrectly referred to as the first German massacre in Italy during the war.<ref name="Boves" >{{cite web |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=29&lang=en |title=BOVES, 19.09.1943 |publisher=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |date= |website= |access-date=24 September 2018 |language=Italian |trans-title=}}</ref> |- |[[Caiazzo massacre]] |13 October 1943 |[[Caiazzo]] |{{hs|00022}}22 |[[3rd Panzergrenadier Division]] |Massacre of 22 civilians, noted for it's brutality and the controversial court case involving the main perpetrator 50 years later.<ref name="Caiazzo" >{{cite web |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=371&lang=en |title=Monte Carmignano, Caiazzo, 13.10.1943 |publisher=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |date= |website= |access-date=23 September 2018 |language=Italian |trans-title=}}</ref> |- |[[Pisino massacre]] |14 October 1943 |[[Pazin]] (now part of [[Croatia]]) |{{hs|00157}}157 |[[1st SS Panzer Division Leibstandarte SS Adolf Hitler|1st SS Panzer Division]] |Anti-partisan operations with aircraft, tanks and ground forces.<ref name= "Pisino" >{{cite news |date= |title=Pazin (Pisino), 04.10.1943|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=5450&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |{{ill|Pietransieri massacre|it|Eccidio di Pietransieri}} |21 November 1943 |[[Pietransieri]] |{{hs|00125}}125 |[[1st Parachute Division (Germany)|1st Parachute Division]] |Mass killing of civilians with explosives after the inhabitants of Pietransieri had refused the order to leave the area and remained in the vicinity of the village.<ref name= "Pietransieri" >{{cite news |date= |title=PIETRANSIERI ROCCARASO 21.11.1943|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=3014&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |{{ill|Monchio, Susano and Costrignano massacre|it|Strage di Monchio, Susano e Costrignano}} |18 March 1944 |[[Palagano]] |{{hs|00130}}130 |[[1st Fallschirm-Panzer Division Hermann Göring]] |Anti-partisan operation in response to increased partisan activity in the area. German troops and their Fascist Italian allies burn villages and indiscriminately execute the male population.<ref name= "Monchio" >{{cite news |date= |title=MONCHIO SUSANO E COSTRIGNANO PALAGANO 18.03.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=5223&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[Ardeatine massacre]] |24 March 1944 |[[Rome]] |{{hs|00335}}335 |[[Schutzstaffel]] |Reprisal for a partisan attack conducted on the previous day in central Rome against the SS Police Regiment Bozen (SD-Gestapo led by [[Herbert Kappler]]).<ref name= "Ardeatine" >{{cite news |date= |title=FOSSE ARDEATINE ROMA 24.03.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=2127&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[Vallucciole massacre]] |13 April 1944 |[[Stia]] |{{hs|00107}}107 |[[1st Fallschirm-Panzer Division Hermann Göring]] |In response to increased partisan activity in the area German troops and their Fascist Italian allies execute a policy of scorched earth by burning villages, raping women and indiscriminately executing civilians to discourage resistance.<ref name= "Vallucciole" >{{cite news |date= |title=VALLUCCIOLE PRATOVECCHIO STIA 13.04.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=3578&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[Memorial Centre Lipa Remembers|Lipa massacre]] |30 April 1944 |[[Ilirska Bistrica]] (now part of [[Croatia]]) |{{hs|00269}}269 |[[24th Waffen Mountain Division of the SS Karstjäger|SS Volunteer Karstwehr Battalion]] |Mass killing of civilians by German occupation troops<ref name= "Lipa" >{{cite news |date= |title=Lipa (Lipa), Elsane, Bistrica (Bisterza) 30.04.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=5465&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |{{ill|Civitella in Val di Chiana massacre|it|Eccidio di Civitella}} |29 June 1944 |[[Civitella in Val di Chiana]] |{{hs|00146}}146 |[[1st Fallschirm-Panzer Division Hermann Göring]] |Anti-partisan operation in retaliation to the killing of German soldiers, where all men in the affected villages were indiscriminately rounded up and executed while the women and children were allowed to leave, except in the village of Cornia, where the original partisan attack took place and women and children are executed as well.<ref name= "Civitella" >{{cite news |date= |title=CIVITELLA IN VAL DI CHIANA 29.06.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=3211&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |{{ill|Cavriglia massacre|it|Strage di Cavriglia}} |4 July 1944 |[[Cavriglia]] |{{hs|00173}}173 |[[1st Fallschirm-Panzer Division Hermann Göring]] |Anti-partisan operation where all men in the affected villages were indiscriminately rounded up and executed while the women and children were allowed to leave.<ref name= "Cavriglia" >{{cite news |date= |title=CAVRIGLIA 04.07.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=3181&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[Sant'Anna di Stazzema massacre]] |12 August 1944 |[[Sant'Anna di Stazzema]] |{{hs|00560}}560 |[[16th SS Panzergrenadier Division Reichsführer-SS|16th SS Panzergrenadier Division]]{{-}}36th Brigata Nera |Mass killing of civilians by German occupation troops and Italian collaborators (16th Brigade)<ref name= "Sant" >{{cite news |date= |title=SANT’ANNA DI STAZZEMA 12.08.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=4908&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[San Terenzo Monti massacre]] |17–19 August 1944 |[[Fivizzano]] |{{hs|00159}}159 |[[16th SS Panzergrenadier Division Reichsführer-SS|16th SS Panzergrenadier Division]] |Anti-partisan operation in retaliation to the killing of 16 German soldiers. Execution of captured partisans and destruction of local villages and execution of the inhabitants.<ref name= "Terenzo" >{{cite news |date= |title=SAN TERENZO MONTI FIVIZZANO 17-19.08.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=4855&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[Padule di Fucecchio massacre]] |23 August 1944 |[[Fucecchio|Padule di Fucecchio]] |{{hs|000184}}184 |[[23rd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|26th Panzer Division]] |Up to 184 Italian civilians as a reprisal for a partisan attack on two German soldiers<ref name= "Eccidio" >{{cite news |date= |title= The responsible |trans-title= |url= http://www.eccidiopadulefucecchio.it/en/i-responsabili/ |language= |work=L'Eccidio del Padule di Fucecchio |location= |access-date=12 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[Vinca massacre]] |24–27 August 1944 |[[Fivizzano]] |{{hs|000162}}162 |[[16th SS Panzergrenadier Division Reichsführer-SS|16th SS Panzergrenadier Division]] |Anti-partisan operation in retaliation to the killing of a German officer. Destruction of local villages and execution of the inhabitants, mostly women, children and elderly who had been unable to escape.<ref name= "Vinca" >{{cite news |date= |title=VINCA FIVIZZANO 24-27.08.1944 |trans-title= |url= http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=4857&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[San Leonardo al Frigido massacre]] |16 September 1944 |[[Massa]] |{{hs|00149}}149 |[[16th SS Panzergrenadier Division Reichsführer-SS|16th SS Panzergrenadier Division]] |Unprovoked mass execution of prison inmates, most of them serving time for minor offences.<ref name= "Frigido" >{{cite news |date= |title=SAN LEONARDO AL FRIGIDO MASSA 16.09.1944|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=4697&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[Marzabotto massacre]] |29 September 1944 |[[Marzabotto]] |{{hs|00771}}770 |[[16th SS Panzergrenadier Division Reichsführer-SS|16th SS Panzergrenadier Division]] |Mass killing of civilians by German occupation troops<ref name= "Marzabotto" >{{cite news |date= |title=Monte Sole (scheda generale)|trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=5705&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |- |[[San Martino di Lupari massacre]] |29 April 1945 |[[San Martino di Lupari]] |{{hs|00125}}125 |[[29th Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|29th Panzergrenadier Division]] |Retreating north in the [[Province of Padua]], under attack by the US Army and [[Italian resistance movement|Italian partisans]], the division randomly executed civilians, took hostages and used them as human shields.<ref name= "Martino" >{{cite news |date= |title=San Martino di Lupari, 29.4.1945 |trans-title= |url=http://www.straginazifasciste.it/?page_id=38&id_strage=3654&lang=en |language=Italian |work=Atlas of Nazi and Fascist Massacres in Italy |location= |access-date=21 August 2018 }}</ref> |}
