Some other articles also cover deaths that might be considered unusual or ironic, including [[list of entertainers who died during a performance]], [[list of inventors killed by their own inventions]], [[list of association footballers who died while playing]], [[list of cyclists with a cycling-related death]] and the [[list of political self-immolations]]. {{TOC limit|2}}
== Antiquity == {{Hatnote|'''Note:''' Many of these stories are likely to be [[wikt:apocryphal|apocryphal]].}} {| class="wikitable" |- !scope="col" | Name of person !scope="col" | Image !scope="col" | Date of death !scope="col" | Details |- !scope="row" | [[Draco (lawgiver)|Draco]] of Athens | | {{circa}} 620 BC | Draco, an Athenian lawmaker, was reportedly smothered to death by gifts of cloaks and hats showered upon him by appreciative citizens at a theatre on [[Aegina]].<ref>Suidas. "[http://www.stoa.org/sol-bin/search.pl?login=guest&enlogin=guest&db=REAL&field=adlerhw_gr&searchstr=delta,1495&filter=CD-Unicode {{lang|grc|Δράκων}}] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103215841/http://www.stoa.org/sol-bin/search.pl?login=guest&enlogin=guest&db=REAL&field=adlerhw_gr&searchstr=delta,1495&filter=CD-Unicode |date=3 November 2015 }}", ''Suda On Line'', Adler number delta, 1495.</ref><ref>{{cite book |page=161 |chapter=Most Unusual Death |title=Felton & Fowler's Best, Worst, and Most Unusual |author1=Bruce Felton |author2=Mark Fowler |publisher=Random House |year=1985 |isbn=978-0-517-46297-3}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Charondas]] | [[File:Illustration of the death of Charondas from 1787.jpg|100px|center]] |late seventh to early fifth century BC | Charondas was a Greek lawgiver from [[Sicily]].<ref name="Murray2007">{{cite book |last1=Murray |first1=Alexander |title=Suicide in the Middle Ages: Volume 2: The Curse on Self-Murder |date=2007 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford, England |isbn=978-0-19-820731-3 |page=128 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=k3YSDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA128&dq=Charondas+suicide#v=onepage&q=Charondas%20suicide |ref=harv}}</ref><ref name="McGlew1993">{{cite book |last1=McGlew |first1=James F. |title=Tyranny and Political Culture in Ancient Greece |date=1993 |publisher=Cornell University Press |location=Ithaca, New York and London, England |isbn=978-0-8014-8387-5 |pages=108–109 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=-w6odgsC9voC&pg=PA108&dq=Charondas+suicide#v=onepage&q=Charondas%20suicide |ref=harv}}</ref> According to [[Diodorus Siculus]], he issued a law that anyone who brought weapons into the [[Ecclesia (ancient Athens)|Assembly]] must be put to death.<ref name="Murray2007"/><ref name="McGlew1993"/><ref name="Groebner2002">{{cite book |last1=Groebner |first1=Valentin |title=Liquid Assets, Dangerous Gifts: Presents and Politics at the End of the Middle Ages |date=2002 |orig-year=2000 |translator-last=Selwyn|translator-first=Pamela E.|editor1-last=Carras|editor1-first=Ruth Mazo|editor2-last=Peters|editor2-first=Edward|series=The Middle Ages Series|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press |location=Philadelphia, Pennsylvania |isbn=978-0-8122-3650-7 |page=131 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=WDNgxuRn6XoC&pg=PA131&dq=Charondas+suicide#v=onepage&q=Charondas%20suicide |ref=harv}}</ref> One day, he arrived at the Assembly after hunting in the countryside with a knife still attached to his belt.<ref name="Murray2007"/><ref name="McGlew1993"/> In order to uphold his own law, he committed suicide.<ref name="Murray2007"/><ref name="McGlew1993"/><ref name="Groebner2002"/> |- !scope="row" | [[Arrhichion]] of [[Phigalia]] | [[File:Pankratiasten in fight greek statue 2 century bC.jpg|100px|center]] | 564 BC | Arrichion of Phigalia, a Greek [[Pankration|pankratiast]], caused his own death during the [[Ancient Olympic Games|Olympic]] finals. Held by his unidentified opponent in a stranglehold and unable to free himself, Arrichion kicked his opponent, causing him so much pain that the opponent made the sign of defeat to the umpires, but at the same time breaking Arrichion's neck. Since the opponent had conceded defeat, Arrichion was proclaimed the victor posthumously.<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Salt Lake Loonie |author1=Brett Matlock |author2=Jesse Matlock |publisher=University of Regina Press |year=2011 |page=81}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=The Journal of Hellenic Studies |author=EN Gardiner |year=1906 |quote=Fatal accidents did occur as in the case of Arrhichion, but they were very rare... |bibcode= 1929Natur.124..121.|volume=124 |page=121 |journal=Nature |doi=10.1038/124121a0 |issue=3117}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Pythagoras]] of [[Samos]] | [[File:Kapitolinischer Pythagoras adjusted.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 495 BC | Ancient sources disagree on how the Greek philosopher [[Pythagoras]] died,<ref>{{cite book|last=Burkert|first=Walter|author-link=Walter Burkert|date=1 June 1972 |title=Lore and Science in Ancient Pythagoreanism|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0qqp4Vk1zG0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Pythagoreanism#v=onepage&q=Metapontum|location=Cambridge, Massachusetts|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=978-0-674-53918-1|page=117|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name="Simoons1998">{{cite book|last=Simoons|first=Frederick J.|date=1998 |title=Plants of Life, Plants of Death|url=https://books.google.com/?id=KEUAbrBoeBAC&pg=PA227&dq=Pythagoras+bean+field#v=onepage&q=Pythagoras%20bean%20field|location=Madison, Wisconsin|publisher=University of Wisconsin Press|isbn=978-0-299-15904-7|pages=225–228|ref=harv}}</ref> but one late and probably apocryphal legend reported by both [[Diogenes Laërtius]], a third-century AD biographer of famous philosophers, and [[Iamblichus]], a [[Neoplatonism|Neoplatonist]] philosopher, states that Pythagoras was murdered by his political enemies.<ref name="Simoons1998"/> Supposedly, he almost managed to outrun them,<ref name="Simoons1998"/> but he came to a bean field and refused to run through it because he had prohibited beans as ritually unclean.<ref>{{cite book|last=Zhmud|first=Leonid|date=2012 |title=Pythagoras and the Early Pythagoreans|url=https://books.google.com/?id=of-ghBD9q1QC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Pythagoras#v=onepage&q=Pythagoras|translator1-last=Windle|translator1-first=Kevin|translator2-last=Ireland|translator2-first=Rosh|location=Oxford, England|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-928931-8|pages=137, 200|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name="Simoons1998"/> Since cutting through the field would violate his own teachings, Pythagoras simply stopped running and was killed as a result.<ref name="Simoons1998"/> This story may have been fabricated by [[Neanthes of Cyzicus]], whom both Diogenes and Iamblichus rely on as a source.<ref name="Simoons1998"/> |- !scope="row" | [[Heraclitus]] of [[Ephesus]] | [[File:Utrecht Moreelse Heraclite.JPG|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 475 BC | According to one account given by Diogenes Laërtius, the Greek philosopher Heraclitus was said to have been devoured by dogs after smearing himself with cow manure in an attempt to cure his [[dropsy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grbs.library.duke.edu/article/viewFile/9121/4593 |title=Death of Heraclitus|author=Fair weather, Janet|year=1973|page=2|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171106082250/http://grbs.library.duke.edu/article/viewFile/9121/4593 |archivedate=6 November 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name="Johnston1806a">{{cite book |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/wondersoflittlew00wanluoft#page/n103 |page=111 |work=The Wonders of the Little World; Or, A General History of Man: Displaying the Various Faculties, Capacities, Powers and Defects of the Human Body and Mind, in Many Thousand Most Interesting Relations of Persons Remarkable for Bodily Perfections or Defects; Collected from the Writings of the Most Approved Historians, Philosophers, and Physicians, of All Ages and Countries |volume=1 |chapter=Chapter XXVIII: Of the different and unusual Ways by which some Men have come to their Deaths §{{nnbsp}}6 |date=1806 |first1=Nathaniel |last1=Wanley |first2=William |last2=Johnston |title=Book I: Which treats of the Perfections, Powers, Capacities, Defects, Imperfections, and Deformities of the Body of Man |location=London |edition=A new |asin=B001F3H1XA |lccn=07003035 |oclc=847968918 |ol=7188480M |quote=Heracl{{bracket|t}}ius, the Ephesian, fell into a dropsy, and was thereupon advised by the physicians to anoint himself all over with cow‑dung, and so to sit in the warm sun; his servant had left him alone, and the dogs, supposing him to be a wild beast, fell upon him, and killed him. |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829203137/https://archive.org/stream/wondersoflittlew00wanluoft#page/n103 |archivedate=29 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Themistocles]] | [[File:Busto di temistocle, da originale greco del V secolo ac, dal decumano presso il casamento del temistocle.JPG|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 459 BC | Themistocles, the Athenian general who won the [[Battle of Salamis]], actually died of natural causes in exile,<ref name=TI138>Thucydides [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0200&layout=&loc=1.138 I, 138] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080405154047/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0200 |date=5 April 2008 }}</ref><ref name="Marr">{{cite journal|last1=Marr|first1=John |title=The Death of Themistocles|journal=Greece & Rome|date=October 1995|volume=42|issue=2|pages=159–167|ref=harv|jstor=643228}}</ref> but was widely rumored to have committed suicide by drinking bull's blood.<ref name = TI138/><ref name="Marr"/><ref name=PT31>Plutarch [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0182;query=chapter%3D%23247;layout=;loc=Them.%2030.1 Themistocles, 31] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080303043624/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0182 |date=3 March 2008 }}</ref><ref name=DSXI58>Diodorus [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0084;query=chapter%3D%23134;layout=;loc=11.59.1 XI, 58] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080924200952/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/cgi-bin/ptext?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0084 |date=24 September 2008 }}</ref> Since bull's blood is not actually poisonous,<ref name="Marr"/> Themistocles cannot have actually died in this way,<ref name="Marr"/> but the legend is widely retold in classical sources.<ref name="Marr"/> The early twentieth-century English classicist [[Percy Gardner]] proposed that the story about him drinking bull's blood may have been based on an ignorant misunderstanding of a statue showing Themistocles in a heroic pose, holding a cup as an offering to the gods.<ref name="Marr"/> The comedic playwright [[Aristophanes]] references Themistocles drinking bull's blood in his comedy ''[[The Knights]]'' (performed in 324 BC) as the most heroic way for a man to die.<ref name="Marr"/><ref>Aristophanes [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0034%3Acard%3D40 84-85] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150611154820/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0034%3Acard%3D40 |date=11 June 2015 }}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Aeschylus]] | [[File:Herma of Aeschylus, Klas08.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 455 BC | According to [[Valerius Maximus]], [[Aeschylus]], the eldest of the three great Athenian [[Tragedy|tragedians]], was killed by a [[tortoise]] dropped by an eagle that had mistaken his bald head for a rock suitable for shattering the shell of the reptile. [[Pliny the Elder|Pliny]], in his ''[[Natural History (Pliny)|Naturalis Historiæ]]'', adds that Aeschylus had been staying outdoors to avert a prophecy that he would be killed by a falling object.<ref name="McKeown2013">{{cite book|last=McKeown|first=J. C.|date=2013 |title=A Cabinet of Greek Curiosities: Strange Tales and Surprising Facts from the Cradle of Western Civilization|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADJpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136&dq=the+unusual+nature+of+Aeschylus's+death#v=onepage&q=the%20unusual%20nature%20of%20Aeschylus's%20death|location=Oxford, England|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|pages=136–137|isbn=978-0-19-998210-3|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name=tortue>{{citation |title=La tortue d'Eschyle et autres morts stupides de l'Histoire |isbn=9782352042211 |publisher=Editions Les Arènes |year=2012}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Naturalis Historiæ |author=[[Pliny the Elder]] |volume=Book X |chapter=chapter 3}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Empedocles]] of [[Agrigento|Akragas]] | [[File:Empedocles in Thomas Stanley History of Philosophy.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 430 BC | Empedocles of Acragas was a [[Pre-Socratic philosophy|Pre-Socratic philosopher]] from the island of [[Sicily]], who, in one of his surviving poems, declares himself to have become a "[[Daemon (classical mythology)|divine being]]... no longer mortal".<ref name="Gregory">{{cite book|last1=Gregory|first1=Andrew |title=The Presocratics and the Supernatural: Magic, Philosophy and Science in Early Greece|date=2013|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic|location=New York City, New York and London, England|isbn=978-1-4725-0416-6|page=178|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AVMBAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA178&dq=Empedocles+claim+god#v=onepage&q=Empedocles%20claim%20god|ref=harv}}</ref> According to Diogenes Laërtius, he tried to prove he was an immortal god by leaping into [[Mount Etna]], an active volcano.<ref>Diogenes Laërtius, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0258%3Abook%3D8%3Achapter%3D2 viii. 69] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105030842/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0258:book=8:chapter=2 |date=5 January 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Meyer|first1=T. H. |title=Barefoot Through Burning Lava: On Sicily, the Island of Cain – An Esoteric Travelogue|date=2016|publisher=Temple Lodge Publishing|isbn=9781906999940|url=https://books.google.com/?id=osrZDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=Empedocles+unusual+death#v=onepage&q=Unusual%20death|accessdate=11 September 2017|language=en}}</ref> This legend is also alluded to by the Roman poet [[Horace]].<ref>Horace, ''[[Ars Poetica (Horace)|Ars Poetica]]'', [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.02.0065%3Acard%3D453 465–466]</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Sophocles]] | [[File:Sophocles pushkin.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 406 BC | A number of "remarkable" legends concerning the death of Sophocles, another of the three great Athenian tragedians, are recorded in the late antique ''Life of Sophocles''.<ref name="McKeown2013"/> According to one legend, he choked to death on an unripe grape.<ref name="McKeown2013"/> Another says that he died of joy after hearing that his last play had been victorious.<ref name="McKeown2013"/> A third account reports that he died of suffocation after reading aloud a lengthy monologue from the end of his play ''[[Antigone (Sophocles play)|Antigone]]'' without pausing to take a breath for commas or punctuation.<ref name="McKeown2013"/> |- !scope="row" | [[Mithridates (soldier)|Mithridates]] | | 401 BC | Mithridates was a Persian soldier who embarrassed his king, [[Artaxerxes II]], by boasting of killing his rival, [[Cyrus the Younger]] (who was the brother of Artaxerxes II), was executed by [[scaphism]]. The king's physician, [[Ctesias]], reported that Mithridates survived the insect torture for 17 days.<ref name=10tbd>{{cite book |chapter=10 truly bizarre deaths |title=Listverse.Com's Ultimate Book of Bizarre Lists |author=Jamie Frater |publisher=Ulysses Press |year=2010 |isbn=978-1-56975-817-5 |pages=12–14}}</ref><ref name=acogc>{{cite book |title=A Cabinet of Greek Curiosities: Strange Tales and Surprising Facts from the Cradle of Western Civilization |page=102 |author=J. C. McKeown |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=2013 |isbn=978-0-19-998212-7 |quote=Ctesias, the Greek physician to Artaxerxes, the king of Persia, gives an appallingly detailed description of the execution inflicted on a soldier named Mithridates, who was misguided enough to claim the credit for killing the king's brother, Cyrus...}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Democritus]] of [[Abdera, Thrace|Abdera]] | [[File:Hendrik ter Brugghen - Democritus.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 370 BC | According to Diogenes Laërtius, the Greek [[atomism|Atomist]] philosopher Democritus of Abdera died at the age of 109;<ref name="McKeown2013p157">{{cite book|last=McKeown|first=J. C.|date=2013 |title=A Cabinet of Greek Curiosities: Strange Tales and Surprising Facts from the Cradle of Western Civilization|url=https://books.google.com/?id=ADJpAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA136&dq=the+unusual+nature+of+Aeschylus's+death#v=onepage&q=Democritus|location=Oxford, England|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|page=157|isbn=978-0-19-998210-3|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name="Diogenesix43">Diogenes Laërtius, [http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.01.0258%3Abook%3D9%3Achapter%3D7 ix.43] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170105030906/http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.01.0258:book=9:chapter=7 |date=5 January 2017 }}</ref> as he was on his deathbed, his sister was greatly worried because she needed to fulfill her religious obligations to the goddess [[Artemis]] in the approaching three-day [[Thesmophoria]] festival.<ref name="McKeown2013p157"/><ref name="Diogenesix43"/> Democritus told her to place a loaf of warm bread under his nose<ref name="McKeown2013p157"/><ref name="Diogenesix43"/> and was able to survive for the three days of the festival by sniffing it.<ref name="McKeown2013p157"/><ref name="Diogenesix43"/> He died immediately after the festival was over.<ref name="McKeown2013p157"/><ref name="Diogenesix43"/> |- !scope="row" | [[Agathocles of Syracuse]] | [[File:Siracusa, agatocle, 25 litre, 310-300 ac ca.JPG|100px|center]] | 289 BC | Agathocles, a Greek [[tyrant]] of [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], was murdered by a poisoned toothpick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/let-us-now-praise-the-romantic-artful-versatile-toothpick-1-46061199 |title=History, Travel, Arts, Science, People, Places – Smithsonian|publisher=}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Philitas of Cos]] | [[File:Antikythera philosopher.JPG|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 270 BC | Philitas of Cos, a Greek intellectual, is said by [[Athenaeus]] to have studied arguments and erroneous word usage so intensely that he wasted away and starved to death.<ref name="9.401e">[[Athenaeus]], ''[[Deipnosophistae]]'', [http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/Literature/Literature-idx?type=turn&entity=Literature.AthV2.p0115 9.401e].</ref> British classicist [[Alan Cameron (classical scholar)|Alan Cameron]] speculates that Philitas died from a [[wasting]] disease which his contemporaries joked was caused by his [[pedant]]ry.<ref>{{cite journal |journal=The Classical Quarterly |volume=41 |issue=2 |year=1991 |pages=534–8 |author=Alan Cameron |title=How thin was Philitas? |doi=10.1017/S0009838800004717}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Qin Shi Huang]] | [[File:Qinshihuang.jpg|100px|center]] | 10 September 210 BC | Qin Shi Huang, the first [[Emperor of China]], whose artifacts and treasures include the [[Terracotta Army]], died after ingesting several pills of [[mercury poisoning|mercury]] in the belief that it would grant him [[immortality|eternal life]].<ref>{{cite book |author=Wright, David Curtis |year=2001 |title=The History of China |publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |page=49 |isbn=978-0-313-30940-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The First Emperor |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-19-152763-0 |pages=82, 150}}</ref><ref name="Nate Hopper">{{cite journal |url=http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/Royalty-and-their-strange-deaths |title=Royalty and their Strange Deaths |author=Nate Hopper |date=4 February 2013 |journal=[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]] |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131119214553/http://www.esquire.com/blogs/culture/Royalty-and-their-strange-deaths |archivedate=19 November 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Chrysippus]] of Soli | [[File:Chrysippos BM 1846.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 206 BC | One ancient account of the death of Chrysippus, a third-century BC [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] [[Stoicism|Stoic]] philosopher, tells that he [[Death from laughter|died of laughter]] after he saw a [[donkey]] eating his [[common fig|figs]]; he told a slave to give the donkey neat wine to drink to wash them down with, and then, "...having laughed too much, he died" (Diogenes Laërtius 7.185).<ref name="Chrysippus">{{cite book|first=Diogenes|last= Laertius |title=Lives, Teachings and Sayings of the Eminent Philosophers, with an English translation by R.D. Hicks|year=1965|publisher=Harvard UP/W. Heinemann Ltd|location=Cambridge, Mass/London}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Eleazar Avaran]] | [[File:Harley3240 f.28 ElephantDetail.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 163 BC | Eleazar Avaran was the brother of [[Judas Maccabeus]]. According to {{Bibleverse|1|Maccabees|6:32-33|NRSV}}, in battle, he thrust his spear into the belly of a king's [[war elephant]], which collapsed and fell on top of Eleazar, killing him instantly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://visual.ly/funniest-and-weirdest-ways-people-have-actually-died |title=The Funniest And Weirdest Ways People Have Actually Died - Visual.ly|website=visual.ly|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430104042/http://visual.ly/funniest-and-weirdest-ways-people-have-actually-died |archivedate=30 April 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Saint Lawrence]] | | 258 AD | The [[deacon]] Saint Lawrence was roasted alive on a giant grill during the persecution of [[Valerian (emperor)|Valerian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=366 |title=St. Lawrence – Martyr|author=Catholic Online|publisher=|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180104045555/http://www.catholic.org/saints/saint.php?saint_id=366 |archivedate=4 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://saints.sqpn.com/saint-lawrence-of-rome |title=Saint Lawrence of Rome|website=CatholicSaints.Info|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150214034736/http://saints.sqpn.com/saint-lawrence-of-rome |archivedate=14 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Prudentius]] tells that he joked with his tormentors, "Turn me over—I'm done on this side".<ref>{{citation |page=42 |title=Enduring Creation: Art, Pain, and Fortitude |author=Nigel Jonathan Spivey |publisher=[[University of California Press]] |year=2001 |isbn=978-0-520-23022-4}}</ref> He is now the [[patron saint]] of cooks, chefs and comedians.<ref>{{citation |title=The Encyclopedia Americana |volume=17 |page=85 |year=1981 |isbn=978-0-7172-0112-9}}</ref> |}
== Middle Ages == {| class="wikitable" |- !scope="col" | Name of person !scope="col" | Image !scope="col" | Date of death !scope="col" | Details |- !scope="row" | [[Ragnar Lodbrok]] | [[File:Ragnar Lodbroks död by Hugo Hamilton.jpg|100px|center]] | {{circa}} 865 | Ragnar Lodbrok, a semi-legendary Viking leader whose exploits are narrated in the ''[[Tale of Ragnar Lodbrok|Ragnars saga loðbrókar]]'', a thirteenth-century Icelandic saga, is said to have been captured by [[Ælla of Northumbria]], who had him executed by throwing him into a [[Snakepit|pit of snakes]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Walter|first=James K.|date=2011|chapter=Ragnars saga loðbrókar |title=The Nibelungen Tradition: An Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/?id=qfizAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA35&dq=Ragnar+Lodbrok+executed+snakes#v=onepage&q=Ragnar%20Lodbrok%20executed%20snakes|editor1-last=Gentry|editor1-first=Francis G.|editor2-last=McConnell|editor2-first=Winder|editor3-last=Müller|editor3-first=Ulrich|editor4-last=Wunderlich|editor4-first=Werner|location=New York City, New York and London, England|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-8153-1785-2|ref=harv}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Sigurd Eysteinsson|Sigurd the Mighty]] of [[Orkney]] | | 892 | Sigurd the Mighty, the second [[Earl of Orkney]], strapped the head of his defeated foe, [[Máel Brigte of Moray|Máel Brigte]], to his horse's saddle. Brigte's teeth rubbed against Sigurd's leg as he rode, causing a fatal infection, according to the Old Norse ''[[Heimskringla]]'' and ''[[Orkneyinga saga|Orkneyinga]]'' sagas.<ref>Translations of the ''Orkneyinga saga'' (chapters 4 and 5), which relates the story, can be read online at [http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/ice/is3/is302.htm Sacred texts] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170329155036/http://www.sacred-texts.com/neu/ice/is3/is302.htm |date=29 March 2017 }} and [http://www.northvegr.org/lore/orkney/001.php Northvegr] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516081857/http://www.northvegr.org/lore/orkney/001.php |date=16 May 2008 }}.</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Edmund Ironside]] | [[File:Edmund Ironside - MS Royal 14 B VI.jpg|100px|center]] | 30 November 1016 | Edmund Ironside was stabbed whilst on a toilet, by an assassin hiding underneath. |- !scope="row" | [[Béla I of Hungary]] | [[File:Béla I (Chronica Hungarorum).jpg|100px|center]] | 11 September 1063 | Béla I of Hungary, when the [[Holy Roman Empire]] decided to launch a military expedition against Hungary to restore young [[Solomon, King of Hungary|Solomon]] to the throne, was seriously injured when "his throne broke beneath him" in his manor at [[Dömös]].<ref name="Turner2011">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iHRuZJDSQLEC&pg=PA8 |title=Dreadful Fates: What a Shocking Way to Go! |date=2011 |page=8 |first1=Tracey |last1=Turner |first2=Sally |last2=Kindberg |publisher=Kids Can Press |isbn=978-1-55453-644-3}}</ref> The King—who was "half-dead", according to the ''[[Illuminated Chronicle]]''—was taken to the western borders of his kingdom, where he died at the creek Kanizsva on 11 September 1063.<ref>Kosztolnyik, Z. J. (1981).''Five Eleventh Century Hungarian Kings: Their Policies and their Relations with Rome''. Columbia University Press. p. 80–81.</ref><ref name="Illuminated_Chronicle_68.96_117">''The Hungarian Illuminated Chronicle'' (ch. 68.96), p. 117.</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Philip of France (1116–1131)|Crown Prince Philip of France]] | [[File:Philip of France (1131).jpg|100px|center]] | 13 October 1131 | Crown Prince Philip of France died while riding through Paris, when his horse tripped over a black pig running out of a dung heap.<ref>Ordericus Vitalis, ''The Ecclesiastical History of England and Normandy'', v. 4, p. 129</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Al-Musta'sim]] | [[File:HulaguInBagdad.JPG|100px|center]] | 20 February 1258 | Al-Musta'sim, the last [[Abbasid]] [[Caliph]] of [[Baghdad]], was executed by his [[Mongols|Mongol]] captors by being rolled up in a rug and then trampled by horses.<ref>{{cite book|last=Frater|first=Jamie |title= Listverse.Com's Ultimate Book of Bizarre Lists|year=2010|publisher=Ulysses Press|location=Canada|isbn= 9781569758175|page=400}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Edward II of England]] | [[File:Edward II - British Library Royal 20 A ii f10 (detail).jpg|100px|center]] | 21 September 1327 | Edward II of England was rumoured to have been murdered, after being deposed and imprisoned by his [[Queen consort|wife]] [[Isabella of France|Isabella]] and her lover [[Roger Mortimer, 1st Earl of March|Roger Mortimer]], by having a [[Horn (anatomy)|horn]] pushed into his anus through which a red-hot iron was inserted, burning out his internal organs without marking his body.<ref>{{cite book |last=Schama |first=Simon |title=A History of Great Britain: 3000BC-AD1603|year=2000 |publisher=BBC Worldwide |location=London}} p.220</ref><ref>[http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=176011 "A red-hot poker? It was just a red herring",] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120002615/http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=176011 |date=20 January 2012 }} ''Times Higher Education''</ref> However, there is no real academic consensus on the manner of Edward II's death and it has been plausibly argued that the story is propaganda.<ref>Phillips, Seymour, Edward II, Yale University Press, copyright 2010. pgs 560–565.</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[John of Bohemia]] | [[File:John of Luxemburg.PNG|100px|center]] | 26 August 1346 | John of Bohemia, after being blind for 10 years, died in the [[Battle of Crecy]] when his companions tied their horses' reins to his own and charged. He was slaughtered in the ensuing fight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://historicalhoney.com/king-john-bohemia-battle-crecy |title=Historical Honey|publisher=|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127203114/http://historicalhoney.com/king-john-bohemia-battle-crecy |archivedate=27 January 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Charles II of Navarre]] | [[File:Charles II of Navarre.png|100px|center]] | 1 January 1387 | Charles II of Navarre known as "Charles the Bad". The contemporary chronicler [[Froissart]] relates that the king, suffering from illness in old age, was ordered by his physician to be tightly sewn into a linen sheet soaked in distilled spirits. The highly flammable sheet accidentally caught fire and Charles later died of his injuries. Froissart considered the horrific death to be God's judgment upon the king.<ref name="Johnston1806b">{{cite book |chapter-url=https://archive.org/stream/wondersoflittlew00wanluoft#page/n111 |page=114 |work=The Wonders of the Little World; Or, A General History of Man: Displaying the Various Faculties, Capacities, Powers and Defects of the Human Body and Mind, in Many Thousand Most Interesting Relations of Persons Remarkable for Bodily Perfections or Defects; Collected from the Writings of the Most Approved Historians, Philosophers, and Physicians, of All Ages and Countries |volume=1 |chapter=Chapter XXVIII: Of the different and unusual Ways by which some Men have come to their Deaths §{{nnbsp}}29 |date=1806 |first1=Nathaniel |last1=Wanley |first2=William |last2=Johnston |title=Book I: Which treats of the Perfections, Powers, Capacities, Defects, Imperfections, and Deformities of the Body of Man |location=London |edition=A new |asin=B001F3H1XA |lccn=07003035 |oclc=847968918 |ol=7188480M |quote=Charles II. King of Navarre, by a vicious life in his youth, fell into a paralytic distemper in his old age, that took away the use of his limbs. His physicians directed him to be sewed up in a sheet that had for a considerable time been steeped in strong distilled spirits, to recover the natural heat of his benumbed joints. The surgeon having sewed him up very close, and wanting a knife to cut off the thread, made use of a candle that was at hand to burn it off; but the flame from the thread reaching the sheet, the spirits wherewith it was wet immediately taking fire, burnt so vehemently, that no endeavours could extinguish the flame. Thus the miserable King lost his life in using the means to recover his health. |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160829203137/https://archive.org/stream/wondersoflittlew00wanluoft#page/n111 |archivedate=29 August 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wJIIAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA5-PA27 |title=A collection of modern and contemporary voyages & travels|page=27|author=Collection|year=1805}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2YxMAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA313|page=313 |title=Chronicles of England, France, Spain, and the adjoining countries: from the latter part of the reign of Edward II. to the coronation of Henry IV|author=Froissart, Jean|translator=Smith, W.|year=1805}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Martin of Aragon]] | [[File:Martín I de Aragón.jpg|100px|center]] | 31 May 1410 | Martin of Aragon died from a combination of indigestion and [[Death from laughter|uncontrollable laughing]]. According to tradition, Martin was suffering from indigestion on account of eating an entire goose when his favorite [[jester]], Borra, entered the king's bedroom. When Martin asked Borra where he had been, the jester replied with: "Out of the next vineyard, where I saw a young deer hanging by his tail from a tree, as if someone had so punished him for stealing figs." This joke caused the king to die from laughter.<ref name=doran>John Doran, ''The History of Court Fools'' (Boston: Francis A. Niccolls & Co., 1858), 377–378.</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Norris|first=Paul N. |title=Patronage and Piety|url=http://www.glossa.fi/mirator/pdf/Morris.pdf Morris.pdf|publisher=Mirator Lokakuu|accessdate=18 May 2011|deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720181412/http://www.glossa.fi/mirator/pdf/Morris.pdf |archivedate=20 July 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |}
== Renaissance == {| class="wikitable" |- !scope="col" | Name of person !scope="col" | Image !scope="col" | Date of death !scope="col" | Details |- !scope="row" | [[George Plantagenet, 1st Duke of Clarence|George Plantagenet]], [[Duke of Clarence]] | [[File:George Plantagenet, Duke of Clarence.jpg|100px|center]] | 18 February 1478 | George Plantagenet, 1st Duke of Clarence, was allegedly executed by drowning in a barrel of [[Malvasia|Malmsey wine]], apparently his own choice once he accepted he was to be killed.<ref>Thompson, C. J. S. ''Mysteries of History with Accounts of Some Remarkable Characters and Charlatans'', pp. 31 ''ff.'' Kila, Montana: Kessinger Publishing, 2004.</ref> |- !scope="row" | Hans Staininger | [[File:Braunau am Inn 003.JPG|100px|center]] | 1567 | Hans Staininger, the [[burgomaster]] of [[Braunau am Inn|Braunau]] (then [[Bavaria]], now [[Austria]]), died when he broke his neck by tripping over his own beard.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hall |first1= Charles Winslow |title=The Nobility of the Trades: Barbers and Hairdressers|journal= National Magazine|volume=32 |issue=1 |page=472 |date=April 1910}}</ref> The beard, which was {{convert|4.5|ft}} long at the time, was usually kept rolled up in a leather pouch.<ref>{{cite web |title=HowStuffWorks – 10 Bizarre Ways to Die|url=http://science.howstuffworks.com/life/human-biology/10-ways-to-die3.htm|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140217225516/http://science.howstuffworks.com/life/human-biology/10-ways-to-die3.htm |archivedate=17 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Tycho Brahe]] | [[File:Tycho Brahe.JPG|100px|center]] | 24 October 1601 | Tycho Brahe contracted a bladder or kidney ailment after attending a banquet in Prague, and died eleven days later. According to [[Johannes Kepler|Kepler]]'s first-hand account, Brahe had refused to leave the banquet to relieve himself because it would have been a breach of etiquette.<ref>{{cite news |author=John Tierney |title=Murder! Intrigue! Astronomers? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/30/science/30tierney.html |quote=At the time of Tycho's death, in 1601, the blame fell on his failure to relieve himself while drinking profusely at the banquet, supposedly injuring his bladder and making him unable to urinate. |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=29 November 2010 |accessdate=30 November 2010 |authorlink=John Tierney (journalist) |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219195755/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/30/science/30tierney.html |archivedate=19 December 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>Thoren ([[#VET|1990]], p.[https://books.google.com/books?id=F5a83U4B8XkC&pg=PA468 468–69])</ref> After he had returned home he was no longer able to urinate, except eventually in very small quantities and with excruciating pain.<ref>(Dreyer, ''Tycho Brahe: A Picture of Scientific Life and Work in the Sixteenth Century.'', p.[https://books.google.com/books?id=ywaut_U5q00C&pg=PA309 309]).</ref> |}
== Early modern period == {| class="wikitable" |- !scope="col" | Name of person !scope="col" | Image !scope="col" | Date of death !scope="col" | Details |- !scope="row" | [[Thomas Urquhart]] | [[File:ThomasUrquhart.png|100px|center]] | 1660 | Thomas Urquhart, a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] aristocrat, [[polymath]] and first translator of [[François Rabelais]]'s writings into English, is said to have died laughing upon hearing that [[Charles II of England|Charles II]] had taken the throne.<ref>{{cite book |title=Rabelais in English Literature |last=Brown |first=Huntington |isbn=978-0-7146-2051-0 |publisher=Routledge |page=126 |year=1968}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The History of Scottish Poetry |publisher=Edmonston & Douglas |year=1861 |page=539}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | James Betts | | 1667 | James Betts died from [[asphyxiation]] after being sealed in a [[cupboard]] by Elizabeth Spencer, at [[Corpus Christi College, Cambridge]] in an attempt to hide him from her father, [[John Spencer (Master of Corpus Christi College, Cambridge)|John Spencer]].<ref name=Rackham>{{cite book|last=Rackham |first=Oliver |authorlink = Oliver Rackham |title= Treasures of Silver at Corpus Christi College |publisher=Cambridge University Press |year=2002 |isbn=978-0-521-81880-3}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Guiley|first=Rosemary Ellen |title= The Encyclopedia of Ghosts and Spirits |publisher=Checkmark books|edition=2nd |year=2000 |isbn=978-0-8160-4086-5}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Molière]] | [[File:Pierre Mignard - Portrait de Jean-Baptiste Poquelin dit Molière (1622-1673) - Google Art Project (cropped).jpg|100px|center]] | 17 February 1673<ref name="Burke2008"/> | The French playwright Molière suffered a [[pulmonary hemorrhage]] caused by [[tuberculosis]] while playing the character Argan, a severe [[Hypochondriasis|hypochondriac]], in his own play ''[[The Imaginary Invalid|Le malade imaginaire]]'' (''The Imaginary Invalid'').<ref name="Burke2008">{{cite book|last1=Burke|first1=David|chapter=The Literary Right Bank |title=Writers In Paris: Literary Lives in the City of Light|date=2008|publisher=Counterpoint |location=Berkeley, California|isbn=978-1-59376-157-8 |page=171|url=https://books.google.com/?id=zwbOBPa7cPYC&pg=PA171&dq=Moliere+death+Le+malade+imaginaire+hemorrhage#v=onepage&q=Moliere%20death%20Le%20malade%20imaginaire%20hemorrhage|ref=harv}}</ref><ref name="Walsh">{{cite book |last1=Walsh |first1=Kieran|chapter=38: The Characters (in Silhouette) from Molière's Play ''Le malade imaginaire'' |title=Medical Education: A History in 100 Images |date=2016 |publisher=CRC Press |location=Boca Raton, Florida |isbn=978-1-4987-5197-1|pages=83–84|url=https://books.google.com/?id=pO0bDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA84&dq=Moliere+death+Le+malade+imaginaire+hemorrhage#v=onepage |ref=harv}}</ref> He disguised his convulsion as part of his performance and finished out the show,<ref name="Burke2008"/> which included a scene in which the character he was playing faked his own death to find out how his wife really felt about him.<ref name="Burke2008"/><ref>{{cite book |last1=Scott |first1=Virginia |title=Molière: A Theatrical Life |date=2000 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge, England |isbn=978-0-521-78281-4 |pages=242–243 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=gLraAyhMePEC&pg=PA242&dq=Moliere+death+Le+malade+imaginaire+hemorrhage#v=onepage&q=Moliere%20death%20Le%20malade%20imaginaire%20hemorrhage |ref=harv}}</ref> After the show, Molière's actual wife, who played the daughter of his character, realized that he really was ill<ref name="Burke2008"/> and carried him across the street to their house in the same chair he had pretended to die in as part of the performance.<ref name="Burke2008"/> He began coughing up blood and she sent for a priest to hear him renounce his acting career so he could be buried on sacred ground,<ref name="Burke2008"/> but Molière died before a sympathetic priest could be found.<ref name="Burke2008"/><ref name="Walsh"/> |- !scope="row" | [[Jean-Baptiste Lully]] | [[File:Paul Mignard - Jean-Baptiste Lully.jpg|100px|center]] | 22 March 1687 | Jean-Baptiste Lully, the French composer, died of a [[gangrene|gangrenous]] [[abscess]] after accidentally piercing his foot with a staff while he was vigorously conducting a ''[[Te Deum]]''. It was customary at that time to conduct by banging a staff on the floor.<ref name=":0">{{Cite book |title = The New Grove French Baroque Masters: Lully, Charpentier, Lalande, Couperin, Rameau|last = Anthony|first = James R.|publisher = W. W. Norton & Company|year = 1986|isbn = 978-0393022865|location = |pages = 16|last2 = Hitchcock|first2 = H. Wiley|last3 = Sadler|first3 = Graham}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Adolf Frederick, King of Sweden]] | [[File:Gustaf Lundberg - Portrait of Adolf Frederick, King of Sweden - WGA13779.jpg|100px|center]] | 12 February 1771 | Adolf Frederick, King of Sweden, died of digestion problems on 12 February 1771 after having consumed a meal of lobster, caviar, sauerkraut, smoked herring, and champagne, topped off with 14 servings of his favourite dessert: [[semla]] served in a bowl of hot milk, called "hetvägg".<ref>[http://www.thelocal.se/6470/20070220/ The lowdown on Sweden's best buns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216203516/http://www.thelocal.se/6470/20070220/ |date=16 February 2008 }} ''The Local'', February 2007</ref> He is thus remembered by Swedish schoolchildren as "the king who ate himself to death."<ref>[http://www.messengernews.net/page/content.detail/id/503630.html?nav=5007 Semlor are Swedish treat for Lent] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308124755/http://www.messengernews.net/page/content.detail/id/503630.html?nav=5007 |date=8 March 2008 }} Sandy Mickelson, ''The Messenger'', 27 February 2008</ref> |}
== 19th century == {| class="wikitable" |- !scope="col" | Name of person !scope="col" | Image !scope="col" | Date of death !scope="col" | Details |- !scope="row" | William Snyder | | 11 January 1854 | William Snyder, a 13-year-old, died in [[San Francisco]], California, when a circus clown swung him around by his heels.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/weird-news/weirdest-deaths-the-13-year-old-killed-by-a-circus-1412109 |title=Weirdest deaths: The 13-year-old killed by a circus clown and other truly epic exits – Mirror Online|author=Rachael Bletchly|date=2 November 2012|website=mirror}}</ref><ref>[https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=64461187&PIpi=69665151https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=64461187&PIpi=69665151] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170806144535/https://www.findagrave.com/cgi-bin/fg.cgi?page=pv&GRid=64461187&PIpi=69665151https%3A%2F%2Fwww.findagrave.com%2Fcgi-bin%2Ffg.cgi%3Fpage%3Dpv&GRid=64461187&PIpi=69665151 |date=6 August 2017 }}</ref><ref>https://horrorhistory.net/2018/01/11/teen-killed-by-being-swung-by-his-heels-by-a-circus-clown/</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Clement Vallandigham]] | [[File:Clement Vallandigham - Brady-Handy.jpg|100px|center]] | 17 June 1871 | Clement Vallandigham, a lawyer and [[Ohio]] politician defending a man accused of murder, accidentally shot himself while demonstrating how the victim might have accidentally shot himself. His client was cleared.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historiclebanonohio.com/?q=vallandigham |title=Death of Clement Vallandigham - HistoricLebanonOhio.com|publisher=|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103215850/http://www.historiclebanonohio.com/?q=vallandigham |archivedate=3 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.civil-war-150.com/tag/clement-vallandigham |title=Fatal Accident to Mr. Vallandigham|journal=The Western Reserve Chronicle|date=21 June 1871|page=2|accessdate=2 November 2013|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103232217/http://www.civil-war-150.com/tag/clement-vallandigham |archivedate=3 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | Henry Taylor | | November 1872 | Henry Taylor, a pall bearer at the [[Kensal Green Cemetery]] in London, tripped over a stone and stumbled as he was carrying a coffin.<ref name="Clay2013">{{cite web|last=Clay|first=Jeremy|date=25 December 2013 |title=10 truly bizarre Victorian deaths|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-25340525|website=BBC News|publisher=British Broadcasting Company|ref=harv|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180519152935/http://www.bbc.com/news/magazine-25340525 |archivedate=19 May 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The other pall bearers let go of the coffin<ref name="Clay2013"/> and it fell on top of Taylor, crushing him to death in front of all the mourners.<ref name="Clay2013"/> The wife of the man whose coffin Taylor had been carrying reportedly "nearly went into hysterics".<ref name="Clay2013"/> |- !scope="row" | [[Sir William Payne-Gallwey, 2nd Baronet]] | | 19 December 1881 | Sir William Payne-Gallwey, a former British [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]], sustained "severe internal injuries" when he fell over and landed on a [[turnip]] while out hunting. He died a few days later.<ref>''"Sir William, so late as Thursday, was out shooting in the parish of Bagby, and in crossing a turnip field fell with his body on to a turnip, sustaining severe internal injuries. All that medical aid could do was done, but with Sir William's failing health he gradually sank, and died, as stated above, about ten o'clock yesterday morning."'' {{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/391692319 |title=DEATH OF SIR WILLIAM PAYNE GALLWEY|publisher=''[[Northern Echo]]''|date=20 December 1881|access-date=28 October 2018}}</ref><ref>''"It was 133 years ago, on 19 December 1881, that the Tory MP Sir William Payne-Gallwey was out shooting in Bagby, North Yorkshire, when he fell over and landed on a turnip. The impact killed the poor man."'' {{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/andy-mcsmiths-diary-the-enemy-within-chequers-at-sam-cams-delayed-40th-9934549.html |title=Andy McSmith's Diary: The enemy within Chequers at Sam Cam's delayed 40th|publisher=''[[The Independent]]''|date=18 December 2014|access-date=28 October 2018}}</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Allan Pinkerton]] | [[File:Allan Pinkerton-retouch.jpg|100px|center]] | 1 July 1884 | Allan Pinkerton, the founder of the [[Pinkerton Detective Agency]], was in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]] when he tripped on the pavement and severely bit on his tongue.<ref name="Lanis1949">{{cite book|last=Lanis|first=Edward Stanley|date=1949 |title=Allan Pinkerton and the private detective institution|location=Madison, Wisconsin|publisher=University of Wisconsin, Madison|page=170|ref=harv}}</ref> His tongue became infected with [[gangrene]], ultimately leading to his death.<ref name="Lanis1949"/> |}
== 20th century == === 1901 – 1950 === {| class="wikitable" |- !scope="col" | Name of person !scope="col" | Image !scope="col" | Date of death !scope="col" | Details |- !scope="row" | [[Topsy (elephant)|Topsy the elephant]] | [[File:Topsy the elephant.png|100px|center]] | 4 January 1903 | Topsy was executed by poisoning, electrocution, and strangulation. A [[Electrocuting an Elephant|74-second film]] of the electrocution was recorded and preserved. It may have been the first time death was ever captured in a motion picture film.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Daly|first=Michael |title=Topsy: The Startling Story of the Crooked-tailed Elephant, P.T. Barnum, and the American Wizard, Thomas Edison|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CcETAAAAQBAJ|page=333|location=New York|publisher=[[Atlantic Monthly Press]]|year=2013|isbn=978-0802119049|deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180409233900/https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=CcETAAAAQBAJ |archivedate=9 April 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>{{better source|it's hard to judge without further corroboration that that source describes the death as "unusual"|date=April 2018}} |- !scope="row" | Unknown | | Early 1903 | An unnamed person was beaten to death with a [[Bible]] during a healing ceremony gone wrong in [[Honolulu]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Tué à coups de Bible. |url=http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k561072w/f3.item.zoom |work=[[Le Petit Parisien]] |date=28 May 1903 |accessdate=13 April 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160524090112/http://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k561072w/f3.item.zoom |archivedate=24 May 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The victim was being treated for [[malaria]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030272/1903-05-14/ed-1/seq-12/#date1=05%2F01%2F1903&index=16&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Kahuna&proxdistance=5&date2=06%2F01%2F1903&ortext=kahuna&proxtext=&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1 The Sun May 14, 1903]</ref> when his family decided he was possessed by devils and summoned a [[Kahuna]] to exorcise the demons; the Kahuna was brought up on a charge of manslaughter.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016339/1903-05-01/ed-1/seq-5/#date1=05%2F01%2F1903&index=6&rows=20&searchType=advanced&language=&sequence=0&words=Kahuna+kahuna&proxdistance=5&date2=06%2F01%2F1903&ortext=kahuna&proxtext=&phrasetext=&andtext=&dateFilterType=range&page=1 Hilo Tribune May 1, 1903 p.5]</ref> |- !scope="row" | [[Mary (elephant)|Mary the elephant]] | [[File:Elephantmary.jpg|100px|center]] | 13 September 1916 | The day after '''[[Mary (elephant)|Mary]]''', a five-ton cow elephant, killed a trainer for the ''Sparks World Famous Shows'' circus in [[Sullivan County, Tennessee|Sullivan County]], Tennessee, she was [[hanged]] by the neck from a railcar-mounted industrial crane.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Olson|first1=Ted |title=The Hanging of Mary, a Circus Elephant|date=2009|publisher=University of Tennessee Press|location=Knoxville, Tennessee|pages=219–227}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Krajicek |first=David J. |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/fed-circus-elephant-lynched-murder-1916-article-1.2149605 |title='Fed up' circus elephant lynched for 'murder' in 1916 |publisher=NY Daily News |date=14 March 2015 |accessdate=15 September 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160912132944/http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/fed-circus-elephant-lynched-murder-1916-article-1.2149605 |archivedate=12 September 2016 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> |- !scope="row" | Twenty-one people | [[File:BostonMolassesDisaster.jpg|100px|center]] | 15 January 1919 | A large storage tank burst in [[North End, Boston|Boston's North End]], releasing a wave of molasses which killed 21 people and injured 150. This event was later dubbed the [[Great Molasses Flood]].<ref name="Smithsonian">{{cite journal| last = Park| first = Edwards| title = Without Warning, Molasses in January Surged Over Boston | journal = Smi